<div class="footnote-footer" id="footnote-1"><a href="javascript:;" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnoteref-1')">1</a>. An English-languge derivation of the far more complex Nahautl phrase <em>Palancanacatl-tlatlatlauhtiani</em>, lit. &quot;those who speak from a place of rotted flesh,&quot; almost certainly a derogatory nickname. Followers of the MASCC cults were referred to by the far more neutral &quot;Nalacoani,&quot; a corruption of the Sarkic endonym Nälkä. It is worth noting that the first recorded use of &quot;Fleshspeaker&quot; comes in the records of MASCC city-states, suggesting a level of emnity between the two sects. Unfortunately, due to a lack of written records, there is no evidence of Fleshspeaker endonyms.</div>
<div class="footnote-footer" id="footnote-2"><a href="javascript:;" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnoteref-2')">2</a>. Literally translated as &quot;The One Free of Chains&quot;</div>
<div class="footnote-footer" id="footnote-3"><a href="javascript:;" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnoteref-3')">3</a>. In Nahautl, Centzontzalantli, roughly &quot;the countless number between [the stars of the sky]&quot;</div>
<div class="footnote-footer" id="footnote-4"><a href="javascript:;" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnoteref-4')">4</a>. While specific beliefs varied between MASCC sects, it is generally agreed upon that Ion survived his encounter with the Centzontzalantli and went on to overthrow the Daevites, glossed in Mesoamerican accounts as the Teatoatl.</div>
<div class="footnote-footer" id="footnote-5"><a href="javascript:;" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnoteref-5')">5</a>. lit. &quot;Half-flayed and half-rotted&quot;</div>
<div class="footnote-footer" id="footnote-6"><a href="javascript:;" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnoteref-6')">6</a>. lit. &quot;lords of weeping/lamentation&quot;</div>
<div class="footnote-footer" id="footnote-7"><a href="javascript:;" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnoteref-7')">7</a>. Most notably in the explicit identification of Ion with Huitzilopochtli, god of war and human sacrifice.</div>
<div class="footnote-footer" id="footnote-8"><a href="javascript:;" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnoteref-8')">8</a>. As the diligent work of Flores has shown, MASCC elites were considered ritually impure to more conventional religions at the time due to their often extensive Sarkic modifications. As such, they were unacceptable candidates for sacrifice; following conquest, their fate is described thusly: &quot;unclean and hated, they were strangled twice, and their bodies burnt. Rites [were performed] to Tlazōlteōtl [goddess of purification and sin], while their ashes were mixed with salt and scattered to the places of dogs.&quot;</div>
<div class="footnote-footer" id="footnote-9"><a href="javascript:;" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnoteref-9')">9</a>. Like all MASCC cults, the Teocuitlapilcac and Teociplanca cults are named after the post-classical city state in which accounts of their existence were first discovered.</div>
<div class="footnote-footer" id="footnote-10"><a href="javascript:;" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnoteref-10')">10</a>. Several accounts note that tribute by Fleshspeaker city-states such as Huiztlitlama included &quot;the gathering of all written records within the lands of [the city], whereupon they were pitched into a huge bonfire.&quot;</div>
<div class="footnote-footer" id="footnote-11"><a href="javascript:;" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnoteref-11')">11</a>. Specifically, localized around the Yucatan province of southern Mexico. Much has been made of the fact that the first accounts of the Fleshspeaker revival came on the heels of the 1562 Mani Inquisition, ordered by the Spanish bishop Diego de Landa, which culminated in the burning of an estimated 95% of all Maya writings. However, the actual relevance is disputed at best. See chapter 9 for additional details.</div>
<div class="footnote-footer" id="footnote-12"><a href="javascript:;" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnoteref-12')">12</a>. On the question of how such an incredible transfer of ritual and cosmology was possible across vast gulfs of time and space, Esmerian was understandably agnostic.</div>
<div class="footnote-footer" id="footnote-13"><a href="javascript:;" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnoteref-13')">13</a>. Another curious coincidence of the Fleshspeaker-Sarkic iconography, the <em>itlacoani</em> was discovered near the base of the future Széchenyi Chain Bridge. Perhaps history has a sense of symbolism.</div>
<div class="footnote-footer" id="footnote-14"><a href="javascript:;" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnoteref-14')">14</a>. The Sarkic council meeting at Valašské Meziříčí is, of course, infamous for the demise of the Ahlen-Sarkic sect.</div>
